or:#000000;font-size:16pt;padding-bottom:6pt;font-family:"Arial";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}h3{padding-top:16pt;color:#434343;font-size:14pt;padding-bottom:4pt;font-family:"Arial";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}h4{padding-top:14pt;color:#666666;font-size:12pt;padding-bottom:4pt;font-family:"Arial";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}h5{padding-top:12pt;color:#666666;font-size:11pt;padding-bottom:4pt;font-family:"Arial";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}h6{padding-top:12pt;color:#666666;font-size:11pt;padding-bottom:4pt;font-family:"Arial";line-height:1.15;page-break-after:avoid;font-style:italic;orphans:2;widows:2;text-align:left}</style></head><body class="c10"><h2 class="c3 c11"><a name="h.qkbfn8xgaxqn"></a><span class="c9">Risk Management</span></h2><p class="c3"><span class="c2">The objective of Risk Management at ORGANIZATION is to support the decision and prioritization process of selecting the most suitable strategy for each known risk. The process applies for organizational assets.</span></p><p class="c3"><span class="c2">A summary of the objectives of this framework is:</span></p><ul class="c1 lst-kix_b2esl2gqegym-0 start"><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">A guidance tool for ORGANIZATION board of directors in regards to the amount and type of risk affecting the organization</span></li><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">As a prioritization tool to understand which risks require immediate treatment given their possible impact with the end goal of controling risk levels to the desired ones (risk appetite).</span></li><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">Serve as a Business Impact Analysis (BIA) tool for ORGANIZATION business continuity management (BCM) practices.</span></li></ul><h3 class="c0"><a name="h.s32ic9t0na6n"></a><span class="c8">Asset Identification Process</span></h3><p class="c3"><span class="c2">Those assets identified with the following process will serve as input for risk analysis activities.</span></p><h3 class="c0"><a name="h.y2cc9byonifk"></a><span class="c8">Risk Analysis Process</span></h3><p class="c3"><span class="c2">The following process describes the actions and responsibles involved in performing Risk Management around organizational assets.</span></p><ul class="c1 lst-kix_wtovf1vch1ur-0 start"><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">Select one (or optionally more) assets from the previous asset identification exercise.</span></li><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">Identify the most suitable Risk owner for this risk based on the asset ownership or business process involved.</span></li><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">For each item, identify a potential risk, its threats and vulnerabilities. Optionally describe the context upon which this threats and vulnerabilities could materialise.</span></li><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">Based on the subjective knowledge of the risk analyst and the asset owner, define the likelihood and impact this threat or vulnerability could have on the selected asset or its associated process.</span></li><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">Describe trough a classification the likelihood of this Risk being materialized:</span></li></ul><ul class="c1 lst-kix_wtovf1vch1ur-1 start"><li class="c3 c6"><span class="c2">High/Likely (Value = 3): This type of threat has taken place in the past and can re-occur</span></li><li class="c3 c6"><span class="c2">Medium/Moderate (Value = 2): There&rsquo;s no known experience in the organization with this sort of threats but they still it could occur.</span></li><li class="c3 c6"><span class="c2">Rare/Low (Value = 1): &nbsp;The probability of this threat to materialize is very low.</span></li></ul><ul class="c1 lst-kix_wtovf1vch1ur-0"><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">Describe the business impact trough the following classification:</span></li></ul><ul class="c1 lst-kix_wtovf1vch1ur-1 start"><li class="c3 c6"><span class="c2">Confidentiality</span></li></ul><ul class="c1 lst-kix_wtovf1vch1ur-2 start"><li class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">(High = 3): If the threat or vulnerability could lead to legal or contractual issues.</span></li><li class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">(Medium = 2): The confidentiality of the assets would not cause legal or contractual issues, but still could seriously affect new or existing customers and business. Contractual penalties could apply.</span></li><li class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">(Low = 1): The lack of confidentiality could affect reputation. There shouldn&rsquo;t be Legal, contractual or penalties associated with the lack of confidentiality.</span></li></ul><ul class="c1 lst-kix_wtovf1vch1ur-1"><li class="c3 c6"><span class="c2">&nbsp;Integrity</span></li></ul><ul class="c1 lst-kix_wtovf1vch1ur-2 start"><li class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">(High = 3): If the loss of integrity could lead to core processes mal-function, legal or contractual issues.</span></li><li class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">(Medium = 2): The lack of integrity on the asset would not cause legal or contractual issues, but might affect some areas of the business causing delays and non-critical errors.</span></li><li class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">(Low = 1): The lack of integrity is not an issue that could affect the daily delivery of business.</span></li></ul><ul class="c1 lst-kix_wtovf1vch1ur-1"><li class="c3 c6"><span class="c2">&nbsp;Availability</span></li></ul><ul class="c1 lst-kix_wtovf1vch1ur-2 start"><li class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">High (Value = 3): If the threat or vulnerability could lead to unavailability of the core business processes that generate revenue.</span></li><li class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">Medium (Value = 2): The lack of availability on the asset would not lead to legal or contractual issues, but would affect customers.</span></li><li class="c3 c5"><span class="c2">Low (Value = 1): The lack of availability would not cause mayor impact on the delivery of services to customers.</span></li></ul><p class="c3"><span class="c2">Note: Optionally, it might be useful to consult with the legal department, asset owner and business process owner this assets relates to in order to define this value.</span></p><ul class="c1 lst-kix_exw480as11ip-0 start"><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">Calculate the level of risk for each with the following formula: (Sum(risk_magnifiers_of_each_asset_in_risk))*(sum(classification_of_risk))</span></li><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">All risks rated at the value of 10 or less are automatically &ldquo;Accepted&rdquo; since they are considered &ldquo;acceptable levels&rdquo; by the business and do not require (although they can have) any further treatment. For all other risks, decide with the asset and business owner if applicable what options exist for the Risk treatment (Accept, Mitigate, Transfer).</span></li></ul><ul class="c1 lst-kix_exw480as11ip-1 start"><li class="c3 c6"><span class="c2">If the decision is to accept, transfer or eliminate the risk then a Risk Exception must be created and asociated with the risk. The residual risk in this case is %100 (with the exception of eliminating the risk, in which case the residual is %0).</span></li><li class="c3 c6"><span class="c2">If the decision is to mitigate the risk, then select a mitigation control or a project that will be used to manage and control the tasks. The residual risk left is %100 if there are no </span></li></ul><ul class="c1 lst-kix_exw480as11ip-0"><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">Once the risk treatment decision has been completed, the risk owner and the security specialist must agree on the amount of residual risk left in terms of percentages and risk points.</span></li><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">If the residual risk exceeds 10 points, an exception could be optionally created in order to record that the remaining residual risk is accepted.</span></li><li class="c3 c4"><span class="c2">Define a review date for the risk</span></li></ul><h3 class="c0"><a name="h.yvjjhubdasou"></a><span class="c8">&nbsp;</span></h3><p class="c3 c7"><span></span></p></body></html>
